# NextEco

![CI](https://github.com/NEXTON/nexteco/actions/workflows/ci.yml/badge.svg)
![Python](https://img.shields.io/badge/python-3.10%2B-blue)
![License](https://img.shields.io/badge/license-MIT-green)

![NextEco](assets/logo.png)

**NextEco** helps any software repository answer one practical question early and honestly:

> **What does this code cost to run in money, time, energy, and CO2?**

It is a small, repository-native subsystem built around:
- one canonical unit of work
- one YAML source of truth
- one generated Markdown report
- one validation pass
- one benchmark path

## The important questions, answered early

### Is this for Python only?
No.

The CLI is written in Python because Python is a pragmatic packaging language for developer tooling, but **NextEco works for repositories in any programming language** as long as the repository can define a canonical unit of work and measure or estimate it.

Typical fits include:
- Python
- JavaScript / TypeScript
- Go
- Rust
- Java
- Kotlin
- C / C++
- C#
- PHP
- Ruby
- Swift
- Scala
- Bash-heavy repos
- polyglot monorepos

If a repo can answer questions like “one request”, “one batch job”, “one inference”, “one build”, or “one evaluation run”, NextEco can model it.

### Is this for AI repos only?
No.

It is for **all repositories**, not only AI repositories.

That said, it is especially useful for AI systems because AI stacks often combine:
- local compute
- external APIs
- long runtimes
- model inference
- geography-sensitive energy and CO2 assumptions

So NextEco is **general-purpose**, while remaining very relevant to AI and ML work.

### Is this for infra teams?
Yes, and not only for infra teams.

It is for **everybody who creates, runs, reviews, or maintains projects**:
- infra teams
- backend teams
- ML / AI teams
- consulting teams
- maintainers
- technical auditors
- engineering managers
- solution architects

If someone might ask “what does this cost to run?” then NextEco is for them.

### Is this just a YAML templating tool?
No.

YAML is used as a **source of truth for reproducibility and reviewability**, not as the product itself.

NextEco gives you a sound workflow for answering cost / time / energy / CO2 questions by combining:
- explicit assumptions
- measured values when available
- estimated values when necessary
- provenance metadata
- arithmetic validation
- generated human-readable reports
- benchmarkable workflows

The YAML file is there so the result can live in the repository, be reviewed in pull requests, and remain understandable over time.

### Why would I use this instead of a spreadsheet?
Because a spreadsheet usually stores results, while **NextEco helps you connect those results to the actual behavior of the repository**.

In practice, NextEco supports a lightweight form of **dynamic program analysis**:
- you define a canonical unit of work
- you run or benchmark that unit of work
- you collect runtime evidence from the program or its environment
- you combine those measurements with explicit cost and carbon assumptions
- you validate the arithmetic and render the result into documentation

So this is not just “cells with numbers.”
It is a repository-native bridge between:
- program execution
- benchmark evidence
- pricing assumptions
- engineering documentation

## Who this is for

NextEco is for teams who want cost-of-running to become a normal engineering concern instead of an ad hoc conversation.

It is useful when you want to:
- document the cost of one representative request or job
- compare scenarios
- separate local compute from external API spend
- keep estimates honest
- make review easier for humans and AI agents
- leave behind a maintainable subsystem instead of a one-off note

## Quick start

```bash
pip install .
nexteco init --template min
nexteco validate cost_of_running.yaml
nexteco render cost_of_running.yaml --output cost_of_running.md
python scripts/benchmark_render.py cost_of_running.yaml --iterations 10
```

## What you get

- a Python CLI
- reusable YAML templates
- validation logic
- readable Markdown report generation
- benchmark helpers
- tests
- examples
- documentation for multiple audiences
- an embedded skill for agent-native workflows

